library(leaps)

Concrete_Data <- read.csv("Concrete_data.csv")

Concrete_Data[Concrete_Data == 0] <- 0.0001

cement <- Concrete_Data$X540.0
slag <- Concrete_Data$X0.0
flyAsh <- Concrete_Data$X0.0.1
water <- Concrete_Data$X162.0
superplasticizer <- Concrete_Data$X2.5
coarseAggregate <- Concrete_Data$X1040.0
fineAggregate <- Concrete_Data$X676.0
age <- Concrete_Data$X28

strength <- Concrete_Data$X79.99

NOTE: We needed to replace instances of 0 with 0.0001 for powerTransform. Or else we would have recieved this error code: “Error in bc1(out[, j], lambda[j]) : First argument must be strictly positive.”

I started off my analysis by creating scatterplots.

pairs( ~ strength + cement + slag + flyAsh + water + superplasticizer + coarseAggregate + fineAggregate + age)

I can’t read this scatterplot, so I decided to run pairs() multiple times.

I’ve already decided that strength would be my response variable, due to it’s interest in our scientific study. So I’ve checked every scatterplot with strength.

pairs( ~ strength + cement + slag)

pairs( ~ strength + flyAsh + water)

pairs( ~ strength + superplasticizer + coarseAggregate)

pairs( ~ strength + fineAggregate + age)

I could only see a linear trend on strength with age and cement.

mod.full <- lm(strength~ cement + slag + flyAsh + water + superplasticizer + coarseAggregate + fineAggregate + age)
avPlots(mod.full)

These avPlots indicate that fineAggregates and coarseAggregates don’t contain any additional useful information after considering the effect of the other predictors. The avPlots also support my previous claim that age and cement have strong relations with strength.

I’m suspicious that fineAggregate or coarseAggregate could have only become useless after considering each other. Maybe, without the other in consideration, one of these two could have been still been useful after considering the rest of the predictors. So I’ve conducted 2 Partial F Tests.

F test: F = \[T^2\] where T ~ \[T_{n-p-1}\]

(From here on out, associate \(x_i\) with Concrete_Data$Vi… i.e the order in which the predictors are listed above and in the READ.ME is the order of ‘i’)

\[Y_i\] = \(\beta_0\) + \(\beta_1x_{i1}\) + \(\beta_2x_{i2}\) + \(\beta_3x_{i3}\) + \(\beta_4x_{i4}\) + \(\beta_5x_{i5}\) + \(\beta_8x_{i8}\)

We can see that fineAggregates and coarseAggregates are left out of this model, supporting the implication the avPlots and F tests gave us.

summary.reg$bic
## [1] -274.8356 -421.7238 -648.8495 -802.2174 -928.1462 -930.1897 -923.6441

When considering BIC as criteria, we want models with the value closest to q, or just the smallest values. Models 6,5,7, and 8 have the smallest values. They are pretty close to each other.

Model 6 seems to be a top contender in terms of adjusted \(R^2\), \(C_p\)-statistic, and BIC. Model 6 produces the same model that our Forward AIC, Forward BIC, and Backward BIC stepwise regression methods produced.

Let’s run some diagnostics on that model.

mod.reg.6 <- lm(strength~ cement + slag + flyAsh + water + superplasticizer + age)
plot(mod.reg.6, which = 1)

The Residuals vs Fits plot for the model shows decent Linearity. You can see that the data consistently bounces around the line (e = Residuals = 0). The slope for the line of best fit, on average, is very close to 0, and doesn’t show a strong pattern. This plot also shows a fairly Constant Variance. We can draw equidistant lines from the line (e = Residuals = 0) encapsulating the points evenly.

plot(mod.reg.6, which = 2)

The Normal Q-Q plot shows decent Normality. It has room for improvement. There’s a slight skew. Let’s see what the shapiro.test has to say about the Normality of the model.

test<-resid(mod.reg.6)
shapiro.test(test)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  test
## W = 0.9957, p-value = 0.005534

\[H_0\]: The vector is normal. vs \[H_A\]: The vector is not normal.

Test Statistic: 0.99584

Since the p-value is 0.006998, less than 0.1, we reject \[H_0\]

The vector that we passed into the test was the residuals of the model. Since the test determined the residuals do not follow a normal distribution, this model violates Normality.

Let’s see if adding 1 interaction term can improve Normality. I’m not going to investigate further than 1 term, for the sake of simplicity.

mod.reg.6.interaction <- lm(strength~ cement + slag + flyAsh + water + superplasticizer + age + water*superplasticizer)
anova(mod.reg.6, mod.reg.6.interaction)

Test Statistic: 30.368

Since the p-value is 4.524e-08, much smaller than any conventional alpha, we reject \[H_0\].

This means that \(\beta_{45}\) 0, and that the interaction term water*superplasticizer can be added to the model.

I manually went through every possible combination (5 + 4 + 3 + 2 + 1) of possible interaction terms to determine which interaction term would pass this test, and also improve normality. The following Shapiro-Wilk test shows thatwater*superplasticizer improved normality by a lot.

test<-resid(mod.reg.6.interaction)

Let’s try some transformations to improve the Normality of the model.

trans <- powerTransform(cbind(X540.0, X0.0, X0.0.1, X162.0, X2.5, X28) ~ 1, Concrete_Data)

The powerTransform function gives us \(\lambda\) for multiple boxCox transformations. It’s a standard to round \(\lambda\) to the nearest 0.5.

Let’s apply all of the \(\lambda's\) to our data, and then take a boxCox transformation to our response.

cement.t <- (((cement**0.5) - 1 )/0.5)
slag.t <- log(slag)
flyAsh.t <- log(flyAsh)
water.t <- water
superplasticizer.t <- log(superplasticizer)
age.t <- log(age)

mod.reg.6.transform <- lm(strength~ cement.t + slag.t + flyAsh.t + water.t + superplasticizer.t + age.t)


boxCox(mod.reg.6.transform)

The optimal \(\lambda\) is the maximum of the log-likelihood function. From the plot, we can see that it’s maximized around \(\lambda\) = 0.5. We’ll use this value to transform our response variable, to try to improve normality.

strength.t <- ((strength**0.5) - 1 )/0.5

mod.reg.6.transform <- lm(strength.t~ cement.t + slag.t + flyAsh.t + water.t + superplasticizer.t + age.t)


test<-resid(mod.reg.6.transform)
shapiro.test(test)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  test
## W = 0.9971, p-value = 0.05941

\[H_0\]: The vector is normal. vs \[H_A\]: The vector is not normal.

Test Statistic: 0.99714

Since the p-value is 0.06361, less than 0.1, we reject \[H_0\]

Normality has improved a lot, but it’s still being violated. For this test, it’s said in Royston (1995) to be adequate for p.value < 0.1 (see ?shapiro.test). So let’s improve past 0.1

Let’s try removing outliers. Now is a good time to do so, because we just finished our transformations.

I’m going to try to add an interaction term, but this time, with the transformed predictors. Like I did earlier, I’m going to manually iterate through possible combinations until I get an optimal interaction term.

mod.reg.6.transform.interaction <- lm(strength.t~ cement.t + slag.t + flyAsh.t + water.t + superplasticizer.t + age.t + flyAsh.t*age.t)
